Statistical machine learning, Lab 11

Classical methods for classification

The aim of this lab is to learn to use R for fitting classical methods for classification and analyzing fit

Fitting a logistic regression model

Logistic regression is a special case of more general class of generalized linear models and can be fitted with glm command, supplying parameter family=binomial(). Using this command is similar to fitting linear model with lm() command. In the tidymodels framework, logistic regression model can be specified with logistic_reg() command, which can later be fitted by constructing appropriate workflow and using fit() command for that workflow. It is important to take into account that glm command allows the response variable to be either numeric (0 or 1) or a factor variable; in tidymodels framework fitting logistic_reg() models requires the outcome to be a factor variable with two levels.

To have predicted probabilities attached to data frame, it is possible to add a variable with mutate(new_var=predict(model,type="response")) or use augment(model, type.predict="response") or use augment(fitted_workflow,new_data=data) if a workflow was fitted.     • If we fit a logistic regression model, then we can construct different classifiers by predicting class for level 1 when estimated probability for that level is larger than a cut-off value \(a\) and class of level 0 otherwise. When we want to minimize classification errors then for correct estimates of the probability the best cut-off value is 0.5 and often the classification by logistic regression is done according to this level. Use conf_mat() command to find the confusion matrix in the case we use default classification rule in the case of iris data. Also find confusion matrix when we consider the error of predicting incorrectly class 1 is 4 times smaller than predicting incorrectly class 0 (cutoff is then \(\frac{1}{5}\)).

      data_pred=augment(wf2_fitted,new_data=iris_mod2)
data_pred|>conf_mat(Species_virginica,.pred_class)
      ##           Truth
## Prediction yes no
##        yes  49  1
##        no    1 99
      data_pred|>mutate(.pred_class=factor(if_else(.pred_yes>1/5,"yes","no"),levels=c("yes","no")))|>conf_mat(Species_virginica,.pred_class)
      ##           Truth
## Prediction yes no
##        yes  50  4
##        no    0 96

Fitting linear discriminant analysis models

Command for fitting Linear Discriminant Analysis model is lda() in the MASS library. Unfortunately some commands in this library overwrite corresponding commands from tidyverse, which may cause problems if we want to manipulate data frames. So, instead of loading this library , I recommend to use use the command in the form MASS::lda(). The predictions for classes can be obtained by predict(model)$class and computed class probabilities can be obtained by predict(model)$posterior. Note that the methods may not work if some classes have several locations of concentration. In order to fit the same model using tidymodels framework, one should install the package discrim and use the command discrim_linear().

Quadratic discriminant analysis

For fitting quadratic discriminant analysis model we use tidymodels framework with discrim_quad() from discrimpackage.

  • Exercise 4 Fit both LDA and QDA models to dataset Lab11_data.csv by using tidymodels framework. Compute confusion matrix for both methods using predictions on the same data which was used for fitting. Produce also a plot which shows how prediction class changes by forming a set of new values for predictors which cover the smallest rectangular area covering the original data. (Hint - commands seq and expand_grid may simplify creation of this data set)

Solution:

  Lab11_data=read_csv("Lab11_data.csv",col_types="nnf")
  colnames(Lab11_data)[3]<-"Class"
  spec_lda=discrim_linear()
  rec_lda=recipe(Class~X1+X2,data=Lab11_data)
  wf_lda=workflow()|>add_recipe(rec_lda)|>add_model(spec_lda)
  wf_lda_fitted=wf_lda|>fit(Lab11_data)#lda(default~income+balance,data=Default)
  pred_lda=augment(wf_lda_fitted,new_data=Lab11_data)
  conf_mat(pred_lda,truth=Class,estimate=.pred_class)
##           Truth
## Prediction   1   2   3
##          1 144   3   2
##          2  16 234   0
##          3   0   3 118
  npoints=100
  X1=seq(min(Lab11_data$X1),max(Lab11_data$X1),length.out=npoints)
  X2=seq(min(Lab11_data$X2),max(Lab11_data$X2),length.out=npoints)
  pred_data=expand_grid(X1,X2)
  ggplot(augment(wf_lda_fitted,new_data=pred_data),aes(x=X1,y=X2,color=.pred_class))+geom_point()+geom_point(data=Lab11_data,aes(x=X1,y=X2,shape=Class),color="black")+coord_fixed()

  spec_qda=discrim_quad()
  rec_qda=recipe(Class~X1+X2,data=Lab11_data)
  wf_qda=workflow()|>add_recipe(rec_qda)|>add_model(spec_qda)
  wf_qda_fitted=wf_qda|>fit(Lab11_data)#lda(default~income+balance,data=Default)
  conf_mat(augment(wf_qda_fitted,new_data=Lab11_data),truth=Class,estimate=.pred_class)
##           Truth
## Prediction   1   2   3
##          1 149   6   0
##          2  11 234   0
##          3   0   0 120
  ggplot(augment(wf_qda_fitted,new_data=pred_data),aes(x=X1,y=X2,color=.pred_class))+geom_point()+geom_point(data=Lab11_data,aes(x=X1,y=X2,shape=Class),color="black")+coord_fixed()

  #plot for predicted probability of class 1
  ggplot(augment(wf_qda_fitted,new_data=pred_data),aes(x=X1,y=X2,color=.pred_1))+geom_point()+geom_point(data=Lab11_data,aes(x=X1,y=X2,shape=Class),color="black")+coord_fixed()
